abstract: New York welcomed the advent of the second year of the twentieth century in characteristic manner. The most demonstrative part of the welcome, as usual, was manifested in the district around Trinity Church, on Broadway, facing Wall Street. Tens of thousands journeyed down to hear the chimes of Old Trinity, and then, in the same old way, blew horns so numerously and vigorously that they could hear nothing but the din of the blowing.

abstract: MANILA, Jan. 1. -- Lieut. Charles D. Rhodes of the Sixth Cavalry, accompanied by two orderlies, when within six miles of Manila to-day came across twenty armed insurgents in a cunrtel or barracks. But in reality he took the cuartel in flank, and drove out the insurgents, capturing two rifles, three revolvers, and some ammunition.

abstract: LONDON, Jan. 13. -- Money was in fair demand to-day and supplies were ample. Discounts were quiet. On the Stock Exchange operators were largely occupied with the settlement in mines and preparations to carry over in other sections to-morrow. The tone was generally cheerful. First-class securities were firm, but consols declined at the close, owing to the belief that the German loan will interfere with the success of the expected British loan.

abstract: ALBANY, N.Y., Jan. 20. -- The National Cycling Association, under whose auspices all of the recent six-day bicycle races have been held, desires the law prohibiting any contestant in a race remaining on the track more than twelve hours amended. Assemblyman Brooks to-night introduced at their request a bill designed to allow contestants to remain on the track the first twenty-four hours and thereafter not more than eighteen hours per day.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Penn., Jan. 21 -- A fresh hit was scored by Henrietta Crosman at the Auditorium to-night in her new role of "Joan o' the Shoals." abstract: PEKING, Jan. 24. -- The Dowager Empress and her Councillors are seriously discussing the engagement of foreign advisers to reorganize the Government. abstract: Troop 2 of Squadron A won the annual five-man carbine shooting match last Saturday night for the third year. The contest was held in the armory, Madison Avenue and Ninety-fourth Street, and the winners led the headquarters contingent by ten points, and Troop 3 was a close third. abstract: CHICAGO, Jan. 27 -- All pits on the Board of Trade went wild to-day. A stampede in May oats forcing liquidations in all markets pressed prices downward in a panicky fashion, and within half an hour from the opening May oats had dropped 5 1/8, May wheat 1 3/8, and May corn 1 3/4. Provisions also were sore hit.

abstract: BERLIN, Jan. 27 -- The Conservative journals here have been singularly silent in regard to the approaching visit of Prince Henry of Prussia to America, which the old aristocracy looks upon coldly. abstract: WASHINGTON, Jan. 27 -- Senator Morgan was overruled in the meeting to-day of the Senate Committee on Interoceanic Canals. The committee refused to order a report favorable to the Nicaragua route for the Isthmian canal and decided it would investigate thoroughly the Panama route before it would make any recommendations with respect to the construction of the canal.

abstract: LA CROSSE, Wis., Jan. 30. -- As Jefferson de Angelis was about to go on the stage in "The Royal Rogue" last night he received a telegram announcing his son's sudden death in New York. He went through the play, however, and at midnight left for the East.

abstract: The stones for the walls of the dungeon in which Senator DUBOIS would confine Gen. abstract: BALTIMORE, Jan. 30. -- The late easing in the tone of the Seaboard group was the most notable feature of to-day's trading. The decline was due to the decrease of $26,947 in the earnings for the third week in January. The Brewing issues again figured prominently in the demand, the common stock advancing 1 point, the first bonds 1 4/8 points, and the income bonds three-quarters of a point.

abstract: PARIS, Jan. 30. -- Charles M. Schwab, President of the United States Steel Corporation, was seen here to-day in connection with the Wall Street rumor that he had resigned the Presidency of that concern, Mr. Schwab refused to confirm or deny this report. abstract: The New York Athletic Club hockey team won an easy victory from the Brooklyn Skating Club at the St. Nicholas Rink last night, scoring 7 goals to the visitors' 1.
